commit 2c321e0ff074c440edffd789759430d87777a285
Author: Brendan Jackman <jackmanb@google.com>

mm/secretmem: Use __GFP_UNMAPPED when available

This commit introduces the use of __GFP_UNMAPPED for secretmem page
allocations when supported. This avoids direct map fragmentation and allows
amortizing TLB flushes.

> diff --git a/mm/secretmem.c b/mm/secretmem.c
> --- a/mm/secretmem.c
> +++ b/mm/secretmem.c
> @@ -47,13 +48,78 @@ bool secretmem_active(void)
>  	return !!atomic_read(&secretmem_users);
>  }
>  
> +/*
> + * If it's supported, allocate using __GFP_UNMAPPED. This lets the page
> + * allocator amortize TLB flushes and avoids direct map fragmentation.
> + */
> +#ifdef CONFIG_PAGE_ALLOC_UNMAPPED
> +static inline struct folio *secretmem_folio_alloc(gfp_t gfp, unsigned int order)
> +{
> +	int err;
> +
> +	/* Required for __GFP_UNMAPPED|__GFP_ZERO. */
> +	err = mermap_mm_prepare(current->mm);

Is it safe to rely on current->mm here in the page fault handler? 

In remote access paths such as process_vm_readv or io_uring worker threads,
current->mm might be NULL or point to a different address space than the
faulted VMA. Should this use vmf->vma->vm_mm instead?

[ ... ]

> +static inline void secretmem_vma_close(struct vm_area_struct *area)
> +{
> +	/*
> +	 * Because the folio was allocated with __GFP_UNMAPPED|__GFP_ZERO, a TLB
> +	 * shootdown is required for the mermap in order to prevent CPU attacks
> +	 * from leaking the content. This is the simplest possible way to
> +	 * achieve that, but obviously it's inefficient - it should really be
> +	 * amortized against the normal flushing that happened during the VMA
> +	 * teardown.
> +	 */
> +	flush_tlb_mm(area->vm_mm);
> +}
> +
> +/* Used __GFP_UNMAPPED so no need to restore direct map or flush TLB. */
> +static inline void secretmem_folio_restore(struct folio *folio) { }

This isn't a bug, but this helper is never used in the patch. The explicit
calls to set_direct_map_default_noflush(folio_page(folio, 0)) remain in the
secretmem_fault error path and secretmem_free_folio. 

Does this mean folios allocated with __GFP_UNMAPPED are explicitly mapped
into the direct map before being freed, defeating the intended unmapped
state?

Additionally, if the direct map restoration is replaced with this no-op
helper, how does the scrubbing handle the unmapped memory? In
secretmem_free_folio(), folio_zero_segment() uses kmap_local_folio() which
accesses the direct map virtual address. Will writing to this unmapped
direct map address trigger an unhandled kernel page fault?

[ ... ]

> @@ -66,16 +132,9 @@ static vm_fault_t secretmem_fault(struct vm_fault *vmf)
>  retry:
>  	folio = filemap_lock_folio(mapping, offset);
>  	if (IS_ERR(folio)) {
> -		folio = folio_alloc(gfp | __GFP_ZERO, 0);
> -		if (!folio) {
> -			ret = VM_FAULT_OOM;
> -			goto out;
> -		}
> -
> -		err = set_direct_map_invalid_noflush(folio_page(folio, 0));
> -		if (err) {
> -			folio_put(folio);
> -			ret = vmf_error(err);
> +		folio = secretmem_folio_alloc(gfp | __GFP_ZERO, 0);
> +		if (IS_ERR_OR_NULL(folio)) {
> +			ret = folio ? vmf_error(PTR_ERR(folio)) : VM_FAULT_OOM;
>  			goto out;
>  		}

If filemap_add_folio() fails later in this function (for instance, returning
-EEXIST due to a concurrent fault), the folio is immediately freed via
folio_put(). 

Because the VMA is not closed, secretmem_vma_close() is not called and the
mermap TLB entries are not flushed. 

Could this race leave stale mermap TLB entries behind, allowing continued
read and write access to the freed physical page?

